New script patterns
As I am getting deeper into updating my sandbox I am uncovering more new patterns, where Paradox are replacing existing script with new methods.

So I'm gonna try and cram as many new patterns in to one post as I can, to avoid spreading them out over multiple posts.
The format will be

old pattern
+ new pattern

NOT = { LHS = RHS }
+ LHS != RHS

is_independent_ruler = no
+ top_liege != this
is_independent_ruler = yes
+ top_liege = this
NOTE confirmation that this works both ways, which should be obvious but you never know 😉

is_landless_adventurer = yes
+ has_government = landless_adventurer_government

has_government = landless_adventurer_government
+ government_has_flag = government_is_landless_adventurer
NOTE This counters the previous pattern change but it wouldn't be Paradox if there wasn't some confusing trends 🤷

num_of_relation_ward >= 1
+ any_relation = { type = ward }
NOTE: This seems to be the case for any num_of_relation_ relationship where the test is > 0 or >= 1, i.e. testing if they have at least 1 of the type of relationship

any_target_title = { count >= 1 }
+ any_target_title = { }
NOTE: This seems to be the case for any any_ list builder where the test is > 0 or >= 1, i.e. testing if they have at least 1 of the type

any/every/ordered/random_held_title = { tier >= tier_county }
+ any/every/ordered/random_held_title = { title_tier >= county }
NOTE The new tier is part of the list builder, not the landed titles as the old one was, best illustrated with an effect list builder
every_held_title = {
    title_tier = county

    limit = {
        holder = scope:rival
        holder.primary_spouse.age >= 21
    }
}
 
New script patterns - continued
any/every/ordered/random_targeting_faction = { limit = { faction_is_type = independence_faction } }
+ any/every/ordered/random_targeting_faction = { faction_type = independence_faction }

ai_has_conqueror_personality = yes
+ has_variable = conqueror
ai_has_conqueror_personality = no
+ NOT = { has_variable = conqueror }

any/every/ordered/random_character_active_contract = { limit = { has_task_contract_type = laamp_join_faction_contract } }
+ any/every/ordered/random_character_active_contract = { task_contract_type = laamp_join_faction_contract }

any_realm_county = { any_county_province = { or = { terrain = mountains terrain = hills } } }
+ any_realm_county = { county_has_province_with_terrain = { terrain = mountains terrain = hills } }
NOTE county_has_province_with_terrain is a new landed title trigger replacing the need to use any_county_province to test terrain but unlike other triggers, this one is implicit OR

capital_county ?= { any_county_province = { any_province_epidemic = { count >= 1 outbreak_intensity < apocalyptic } } }
+ capital_county ?= { has_province_with_epidemic = { intensity < apocalyptic } }
NOTE has_province_with_epidemic is a new landed title trigger replacing the need to use
any_county_province = { any_province_epidemic = {} }

to test a outbreak intensity 
has_variable -- New functionality
This is significant, so deserves it's own post.

Old documentation
has_global_variable - Checks whether the current scope has the specified variable set
has_variable = name
Supported Scopes: none

Old script
nor = {
    exists = involved_activity
    has_variable = homage_liege_scope
    has_character_flag = meditation_character_flag
    has_character_flag = petition_liege_character_flag
    has_character_flag = holding_court_character_flag
    is_being_visited_on_tour_strict = yes
}

New documentation
has_variable - Checks whether the current scope has any of the specified variables set

has_variable = variable_name

has_variable = {
    name = variable_name1
    name = variable_name2
    name = variable_name3
}
Supported Scopes: none

New script
nor = {
    exists = involved_activity
    has_variable = {
        name = homage_liege_scope
        name = meditation_character_flag
        name = local_shrine_rite
        name = petition_liege_character_flag
        name = holding_court_character_flag
    }
    is_being_visited_on_tour_strict = yes
}

It looks weird considering triggers are implicit AND so you would assume that is not semantically the same but take note of the documentation
any of the specified variables

Presumably this is from their performance drive, so this new trigger is more efficient than doing multiple has_variable
